<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Memo</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:14pt; line-height:95%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">Written evidence submitted by the Met Office (IPC0026)</span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:95%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">Summary</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 16.4pt; text-indent:-16.4pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The AR5 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">WGI </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">report </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">on the physical basis for climate change </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">is arguably the most robust report that the IPCC has ever produced - robust in terms of both the quantity and quality of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">evidence, the rigour of the review process, the consistency of the conclusions with previous reports and other independent reviews, and in the increased confidence attached to earlier findings.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 16.4pt; text-indent:-16.4pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Further scientific progress could modify the specific details </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">of assessment statements and this would be reflected in future IPCC assessment reports. However, the AR5 WGI report represents what is probably the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">w</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">orld’s </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">most comprehensive </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">assessment of the current state of scientific understanding on the physical scien</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ce basis of climate change.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:5pt 0pt 0pt 10.06pt; padding-left:6.34pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The IPCC reports are vital in consolidating the science undertaken around the world. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">They</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> provide a consensus for international negot</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">iation on climate issues but do</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> not, and cannot, provide the detail required at the national and regional levels for adaption planning. </span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.06pt; padding-left:6.34pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In addition, the fact that the process takes approximately two years to complete within a five to six year cycle, means the reports cannot capture </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e latest, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">emerging science, nor are they responsive to changing policy and decision making needs. However, the very nature of science means it is always developing and progressing and the UK, like any other </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">n</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ation, needs the latest robust scientific eviden</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ce to underpin its national policy and decision making.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">he Met Office Hadley Centre </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">supports the UK government in just this way</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span></li></ul></ul></ul></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 16.4pt; text-indent:-16.4pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Furthermore, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">reports compiled by the IPCC depend on </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the contributions of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">national capabili</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ty science programmes, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">such as the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Met Office Hadley Centre Climate Programme (HCCP) and the academic research that it facilitates and integrates</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">; t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">he underpinning science and evidence base must be driven forward by domestic science programmes. </span></li></ul></ul></ul></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 14.2pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><br style="page-break-before:always; clear:both" /></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">How robust are the conclusions in the AR5 Physical Science Basis report? </span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The AR5 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">WGI </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">report on the physical</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> basis for climate change</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> is arguably the most robust report that the IPCC has ever produced - in terms of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">both </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the quantity and quality of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">evidence, the rigour of the review process</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the consistency of the conclusions from previous reports and other independent reviews, and in the increased confidence attached to earlier findings.</span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The report was developed by an international team of scientis</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ts who were selected in May 2010</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The processes and procedures</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> underpinning the report are fully transparent and participation is open worldwide to anyone with proven credentials in the field of climate science. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Of particular note is the fact that 529 me</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">mbers of the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> overall AR5</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> writing team, representing 63%</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">were new to the IPCC process, demonstrating </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">how </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">fresh thinking and new approaches are merged with proven processes.</span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The evidence base underpinning the report consists of many independent scientific </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">analyses </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">from </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">a wide range of sources including observations, theoretical studies, paleoclimate records and modelled simulations. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Specifically</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> AR5 WG</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">I</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">cites over 9,200 publications</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> provides a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> comprehensive and extensively reviewed </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">assessment of these analyses. Importantly, the assessment </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">employs formal, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">calibrated uncertainty language in which statements made with high confidence are associated </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">both </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">with </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">high </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">level of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">agreement across multiple lines of evidence and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">also </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">where ther</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e is robust evidence. Therefore, high confidence statements are made only when supported by robust results from multiple lines of evidence. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The report went through a multi-stage</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, thorough and meticulous</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> review process involving expert reviewers and gover</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nments. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Reviewers were able to self-nominate through an open process. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The first order draft of the report received 21,400 comments from 659 expert reviewers and the second order draft received 31,422 comments from 800 expert reviewers and from 26 governmen</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ts. The final government distribution received 1855 comments from 32 governments on the final draft Summary for Policymakers (SPM). Every comment received throughout the review process was responded to individually by the author team.</span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The central conclusi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ons of the AR5 WGI report - that the world is warming, that there is a strong likelihood that the main reason for this warming is human influence on climate, and that continued emissions of greenhouse gases would cause further warming –are entirely consist</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ent with AR4 and are stated with an increased confidence. This rise in confidence stems from additional observational evidence and a new generation of climate models. In addition, the consistency of the evidence across IPCC reports provides additional supp</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ort for the main conclusions of the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">WGI</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> report being robust.</span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Other independent bodies, such as the Royal Society</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and the National Academy of Sciences, have also assessed the evidence basis for climate change in recent years and have reached conclusions c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">onsistent with those of the IPCC.</span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">There is, of course, new science assessed in the AR5</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> WGI</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> report that was not available at the time of the AR4 report</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. For example, the SPM states “</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Cumulative total emissions of CO2 and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">global mean surface temperature resp</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">onse are approximately linearly related”.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> As a result, the IPCC report authors were able for the first time to assess the level of cumulative emissions which </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">they deemed</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> necessary to avoid a particular likelihood of exceeding 2 °C rise in global mean surfa</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ce temperature. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Specifically</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, “limiting the warming caused by anthropogenic emissions alone with a probability of &gt; 66% to less than 2 °C since the period 1861-1880 will require cumulative emissions [to be less than] about 1000GtC.” By 2011 around 515GtC h</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">as </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">already </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">been emitted.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">This is a new conclusion not present in AR4 and is based on multiple lines of evidence published in the peer-reviewed literature reflecting the current scientific understanding on this issue.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Ha</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">ve the IPCC adequately addressed</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> criticisms of previous reports?</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The InterAcademy Council</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> (IAC)</span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> conducted an independent review of the processes and procedures of the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change. The IAC’s report, published in October 2010, recommended a number of measures</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and actions to strengthen IPCC’s processes and procedures.</span><a name="_ftnref5"></a><a href="#_ftn5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> The IPCC </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">was able </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to implement </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">many of the IAC’s 22 recommendations </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">immediately. The</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> remainder </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">were taken </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">under review by task groups </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">since</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> AR5 was already underway and some of the recommendation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s would </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">therefore </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">need to be implemented at a later date.</span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Some of the IAC’s key concerns either focussed specifically on the AR4 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">WGII </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">report, or on methodological inco</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nsistencies between different working groups</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> such as in the communication of uncertainty</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In this context, t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">wo Met Office scientists who were previously Lead Authors in WG</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">I</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> AR4 are now Lead Authors in WGII</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> in AR5</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. In addition,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Met Office scientists have been </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">active </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">as expert reviewers on the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">AR5 WGII</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> report in order to help contribute to i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">mproved consistency across </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">working group</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s and to help support the implementation of the IAC’s recommendations.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">While the IPCC report is the product of people, and therefore not immune to errors of various sorts, the process underpinning the production of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">IPCC reports - including multiple stages of peer review</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> -</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> has helped ensure that the most important conclusions of the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">assessment reports</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> have remained robust to subsequent scientific scrutiny. Following on from the IAC report</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the IPCC has instituted a pr</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ocedure for correcting errors in reports starting with WG</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">I</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> which is documented at </span><a href="https://www.ipcc.ch/pdf/ipcc-principles/ipcc_error_protocol.pdf"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">https://www.ipcc.ch/pdf/ipcc-principles/ipcc_error_protocol.pdf</span></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">It is important to remember </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">also that science is continually progressing and as a result the assessment can and should change to reflect that new understanding. The integrity of each IPCC report should be judged therefore on its robustness in reflecting the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">current</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> state of scientifi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">c understanding. Regarding the main messages coming out of successive IPCC reports, for example on attribution, the level of confidence in many statements has increased as a result of more evidence from new observations, improved climate models and better </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">understanding.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">How much scope is there to question the report’s conclusions?</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The evidence </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">leads to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> a robust scientific consensus on the main headline messages of the report. Clearly, and as part of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">normal</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> scienti</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">fic process (which is inherently sceptic</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">al)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">statements will continue to be challenged as new evidence emerges. Future assessments will reflect scientific progress - including any strengthening or weakening of the confidence levels of statements. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">However, the AR5 WGI report represents what is pr</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">obably the world’s </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">most </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">comprehensive </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">assessment of the current state of scientific understanding on the physical science basis of climate change. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">To what extent does AR5 reflect the range of views among climate scientists?</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The AR5 WGI</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> report </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">represents the range of views among climate scientists who were lead authors of the report and takes into account the many expert review comments. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The lead authors themselves drew on a huge range of evidence (</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">over 9,200</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">scientific publications are cited)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">o form an unbiased, expert summary of the current state of the scientific evidence. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Where there is lack of consensus — and therefore a lack of evidence for robust conclusions — the report reflects this by providing statements with low confidence. This is t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">he case for example on the issue of Antarctic ice sheet loss described thus in the SPM: “due to a low level of scientific understanding there is low confidence in attributing the causes of the observed loss of mass from the Antarctic ice sheet over the pas</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">t two decades.” </span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">A </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">small </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">minority of the climate science community disagree with </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">some </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">of the conclusions from the AR5 WG1 report. However, it is important to note that conclusions in the SPM are directly traceable to the detailed assessment in the report </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">chapters</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and thence to the peer-reviewed literature</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. This is an important aspect of IPCC reports that has been tested and verified in the expert and government review stages, including at the SP</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">M plenary approval in Stockholm</span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The IPCC review process is op</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">en to anyone who self-declares appropriate experience or qualifications, and Met Office scientists have been pro-active in raising awareness of how to participate in the review process, including in social media for</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ums</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> where criticism of climate science an</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">d the IPCC is regularly aired.</span><a name="_ftnref6"></a><a href="#_ftn6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">  A number of individuals who disagree with previous IPCC conclusions took an active part in the review process</span><a name="_ftnref7"></a><a href="#_ftn7">[7]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, and others registered as reviewers</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> but did not submit review comments.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Can any of the areas of the science no</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">w be considered settled as a result of AR5’s publication, if so which?</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> What areas need further effort to reduce the levels of uncertainty?</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">That the climate system has warmed since pre-industrial times can be considered settled as expressed in “warming of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the climate system is unequivocal”. The strength of evidence for the dominant role of human influence on warming since the mid 20</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super">th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> century has now reached a very high level of likelihood (</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">“extremely</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">likely”</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">, greater than 95% certain</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">). </span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">While statements such as “warming is unequivocal”, “human influence on climate is clear” and “continued emissions of greenhouse gases will cause further warming” are expressing aspects of climate change that can be considered settled, further research is n</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">eeded to understand </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">better certain </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">aspects</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> such as the implications of climate change for extreme weather, the regional effects of future climate change, and to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> narrow the uncertainty in climate sensitivity</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. Better u</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nderstanding of these issues is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> importa</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nt to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">quantify </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">better </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the rate of emissions reductions needed to reduce the risks of various forms of climatic disruptions in future.</span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Reductions in uncertainty come from a number of routes: improved land and ocean observations and records, better understa</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nding of the physical processes in the climate – and their inter-relationships and dependencies</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> -</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> increased model resolution and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">inclusion of important Earth system feedbacks. Along with the need to run large ensemble simulations, there is a clear need </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">for</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">supercomputing capacity and infrastruc</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ture</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In particular, understanding climate change and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">its </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">consequences on a regional scale is imperative to provide the underpinning evidence for best allocation of resources to meet the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">adaptation </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">challenges these </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">will bring. Decadal forecasting is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">new and challenging area of research</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> but it is seen as becoming invaluable to policy and decision makers in providing guidance on how near-term trends in warming are likely to evolve and, importantly, what role natural</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> variability of the climate system may play. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The key difference between decadal forecasts and the IPCC climate change scenarios is that the forecasts start from the current state of the climate system and hence </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">can represent the current effects of natural </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">variability, such as those related to the recent pause in global surface temperature rise. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">   </span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In addition, when considering extremes in weather, decadal forecasting has the potential to improve the assessment of the future probabilities of events such as</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> wild fires, flooding and heatwaves</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, which are strongly influenced by natural variability as well as climate change</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. It has already been demonstrated that skilful multi-year predictions of Atlantic hurricane frequency can be produced</span><a name="_ftnref8"></a><a href="#_ftn8">[8]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. Much more remains to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> be done however to fully exploit the regional information in decadal forecasts and indeed in climate predictions on all timescales from months to the end of the century. This is one of the main aspects of the Met Office Hadley Centre Climate Programme. </span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Improvements to the assessment of the impacts of climate change, both in attribution of past impacts and assessing future risks, is also now a core component of the Met Office Hadley Centre Climate Programme. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">These aspects are an important part of the UK’s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> contribution to WG</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">II</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">How effective is AR5 and the summary</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> for policymakers in conveying</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">what is meant by </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">uncertainty in scientific terms</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">? Would a focus on risk rather than uncertainty be useful?</span></p><ol start="21" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">For aspects of the scientific assessment where there is a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> clear consensus, the calibrated uncertainty language works well. The calibrated confidence and likelihood language has allowed uncertainties to be clearly expressed and understood and for there to be comparison of assessment statements throughout the repo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">rt.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> To move from scientific uncertainty to risk assessments requires knowledge of exposure and vulnerability; this is not with</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">in the scope of WGI</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> but instead lies within WG</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">II</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and WG</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">III</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Does the AR5 address the reliability of climate models?</span></p><ol start="22" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Chapter 9 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the AR5 WGI report </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">deals exclusively with the issue of evaluation of climate models. This chapter assesses: climate models and their characteristics; techniques for assessing model performance; experimental strategies in support of climate model evaluation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">; simulation of recent and long-term trends in global models</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> simulation of variability and extremes; downscaling and simulation of regional climate; climate sensitivity and climate feedbacks</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">relating each aspect of model performance to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">credibilit</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">y of model applications</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to different aspects of climate change</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">AR5 WGI concludes that climate models have improved since AR4. Models reproduce observed continental-scale surface temperature patterns and trends over many decades, including the more rapid</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> warming since the mid-20</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super">th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> century and the cooling immediately following large </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">volcanic eruptions. The report also concludes that there has been substantial progress in the assessment of extreme weather and climate events since AR4 and that some important</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> climate phenomena are now better reproduced by models. </span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">At the same time however, the report recognises there remain some deficiencies in climate models. These are particularly at regional scales where the confidence in model capability to simulate surfa</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ce temperature and precipitation is less than for the larger scales, and where the assessment is hampered by observational uncertainties.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Has AR5 sufficiently explained the reasons behind the widely reported hiatus in the global surface temperature record?</span></p><ol start="25" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Noting that papers cited in the report had to be accepted in March 2013, there was relatively little peer-reviewed literature </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">from which</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to assess this issue. Nevertheless Chapter 9 of the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">WGI </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">report does consider in some detail the possible effects of na</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">tural internal climate variability</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> changes in radiative forcing in causing the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">pause. It </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">also considers whether model response error could be responsible for differences between climate models and observations in recent global mean temperature trends. The report’s conclusion is that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">“the observed reduction in surface warming trend over the per</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">iod 1998-2012 compared to the period 1951-2012, is due in roughly equal measure to a reduced trend in radiative forcing and a cooling contribution from internal variability, which includes a possible redistribution of heat within the ocean (medium confiden</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">ce).”</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Recognising that the AR5 timescale would preclude a comprehensive discussion of the pause, the Met Office Hadley Centre produced three linked reports on this topic in July 2013</span><a name="_ftnref9"></a><a href="#_ftn9">[9]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Do the AR5 Physical Science Basis report’s conclusions strengthen or </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">weaken the economic case for action to prevent dangerous climate change? </span></p><ol start="26" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The WGII and WGIII reports and the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> full</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Synthesis will be required in order to take a more comprehensive statement on economic impacts and costs of mitigation and adaptation.</span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Nevert</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">heless, the findings of the observations and attribution section of the report typically strengthen the case that human-influenced climate change is manifest</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ed</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> in many key parts of the climate system, helping to underpin </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">case for action. </span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The total an</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">thropogenic radiative forcing for 2011 is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">44% higher</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">compared to that reported in AR4 for 2005. This is in part due to continuing increases in carbon emissions but also because the latest assessment of aerosol radiative forcing suggests that it is less neg</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ative (i.e. reduced cooling effect) than previously thought. </span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The likely severity of future global warming for a given increase in human-induced radiative forcing, as estimated from climate models, is similar to earlier assessments, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">although there is some evidence that the upper end of the global warming estimates, previously considered in AR4, may now be less likely. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">What implications do the IPCC’s conclusions in the AR5 Physical Science Basis report have for policy making both nati</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">onally and internationally? </span></p><ol start="30" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The report’s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> conclusions provide robust and strong evidence for the effects of human influence on climate. The report also shows that limiting climate change to the UNFCCC agreed global mean temperature target of 2°C above pre-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">industrial will require substantial and sustained </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">reductions of greenhouse gas emissions, and that many aspects of climate change</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, such as sea-level rise,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> will persist for many centuries even if future emissions of carbon dioxide are reduced or stopped.</span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">R</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">eport’s set of agreed conclusions</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> - </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">shared and understood internationally by both scientists and policymakers</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> -</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> provide a vitally important platform to underpin international negotiations on climate issues.</span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">However, the IPCC reports do not, indeed ca</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nnot, provide the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">scientific </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">detail required at a regional and national level to underpin the UK’s adaption planning and policy decision making. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The underpinning science is progressed and driven primarily to meet national challenges and support national po</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">licy. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">This is the role of the Met Office Hadley Centre.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In addition, given that science is always progressing with new understanding, improved modelling and increased and better observational evidence, it is the ongoing national science programs that pro</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">vide the capability with which to meet changing policy needs. This will help answer more penetrating questions on issues such as changing weather patterns (including extremes)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> attribution</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Is the IPCC process an effective mechanism for assessing scien</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">tific knowledge? Or has it focussed on providing a justification for political commitment?</span></p><ol start="34" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The IPCC provides an effective mechanism for determining </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">current scientific consensus </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and is underpinned by a rigorous writing and review process</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. It is hard to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">envisage a radically different process for determining such a consensus that would be as effective. </span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The mantra underpinning IPCC is that it should be policy relevant and not policy prescriptive and this philosophy continues to be adhered to in the report</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s including the AR5 WGI report. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">To what extent did political intervention influence the final conclusions of the AR5 Physical Science Basis summary? </span></p><ol start="36" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Coordinating Lead Authors were present at the final approval session of AR5 WGI and, along with the co-ch</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">airs and additional Lead Authors also present, helped ensure that any changes to the SPM remained consistent with the factual material in the full report. While the meeting involved government representatives, discussions were scientifically based to ensur</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e SPM statements were expressed accurately and in a form understandable by policy makers.  Observers, for example from NGOs, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">were</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> also present but d</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">id</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> not take part in the formal discussions.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Is the rate at which the UK Government intends to cut CO2 emissi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">ons appropriate in light of the findings of the IPCC AR5 Physical Science Basis report? What relevance do the IPCC’s conclusions have in respect of the review of the fourth Carbon Budget? </span></p><ol start="37" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Committee on C</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">limate </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">C</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">hange has already commissioned research </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to examine how the findings of AR5 will affect the global pathway of emissions from which the UK's carbon budgets are derived</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">December 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><a href="http://www.ipcc.ch/pdf/ipcc-principles/ipcc-principles.pdf"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.ipcc.ch/pdf/ipcc-principles/ipcc-principles.pdf</span></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><a href="http://www.ipcc.ch/organization/organization_procedures.shtml#.Uo8hZ5yDq70"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.ipcc.ch/organization/organization_procedures.shtml#.Uo8hZ5yDq70</span></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn3"></a><a href="#_ftnref3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><a href="http://royalsociety.org/uploadedFiles/Royal_Society_Content/policy/publications/2010/4294972962.pdf"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://royalsociety.org/uploadedFiles/Royal_Society_Content/policy/publications/2010/4294972962.pdf</span></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn4"></a><a href="#_ftnref4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">he </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">IAC was </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">created </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">in 2000 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">by the world's</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><span s